                                    Info.
                            








                                I want to update the name on my LifeLock account.
                            





                                If you’d like to update your name due to a simple misspelling:
                            

                                You can call and speak to one of our United States-based agents or submit support
                                request from your online account.
                            

                                Call us at 1-800-LifeLock (1-800-543-3562).
                            

                                or
                            

                                Submit a Support Request through your LifeLock online account with correct spelling.
                            




















                                If you’d like to change your name due to a legal name change:
                            

                                Please send us a note indicating the change you’d like to make along with one of these
                                documents to verify the change. We must have a copy of the official document
                            


                                    Valid government-issued ID with new name such as: a driver's license, passport or
                                    state- issued ID card
                                

                                    Social security card with new name
                                

                                    Court documents petition for name change (with court seal/stamp)
                                

                                    Letter from the Social Security Administration indicating name change
                                

                                    Marriage certificate
                                


                                Unfortunately, we can’t accept documents by email, but you can send the information to
                                LifeLock Document Department via our secure fax line at 888-244-9823 or by mail at:
                            

                                LifeLock, Inc.
                                Attn: Document Department
                                60 E. Rio Salado Pkwy - 4th Floor
                                Tempe, AZ 85281
                            

                                We’ll make the change within a couple of business days and let you know when we’re
                                finished.
                            












                                I am not receiving emails from LifeLock.
                            





                                If you are not receiving LifeLock emails please start by verifying your email address on
                                file is correct by clicking 
                                 Alert Contact Info


                                Once you’ve verified your email address on file make sure to check your email’s
                                spam/junk folders. If you locate any LifeLock emails mark them as ‘not spam/junk’. This
                                will prevent the emails returning to the spam/junk folder in the future.
                            

                                 If you are unable to locate any LifeLock emails in your spam/junk folder, please call
                                us at 1-800-Lifelock (1-800-543-3562) so we can look into it.
                            








                                My information has been compromised and I am a LifeLock member:
                            





                                My credit card or debit card was used fraudulently
                            

                                If you have not already done so, please contact your financial institution immediately
                                to report the fraudulent transactions so they may begin an investigation in regards to
                                your account. Once this has been reported, please call our Member Services Department at
                                1-800-LifeLock (1-800-543-3562). We need to speak with you regarding this matter and
                                collect additional information.
                            

                                I was informed of a breach of my information (no known fraudulent activity)
                            

                                There are several things you can do to watch for fraud at this time:
                            


                                    Monitor your transactions: Keep an eye on the activity on your credit and debit
                                    cards, looking out for any charges that don't seem to be yours.
                                

                                    Report suspicious transactions immediately: If you see something that doesn't look
                                    right, contact the card issuer immediately. The phone number is on the back of your
                                    card. If the transactions turn out to be fraudulent, you will also want to notify
                                    LifeLock. The LifeLock Service Terms and Conditions require that you notify LifeLock
                                    within ninety (90) days of the date you know, or reasonably should have known, that
                                    someone has improperly used your credit/debit cards or bank account.
                                

                                    Watch your credit reports: You can get a free credit report from each of the three
                                    major U.S. credit bureaus each year, and you can pay for more frequent access. Get
                                    more information from the Federal Trade Commission at
                                    
                                        http://www.consumer.ftc.gov/articles/0155-free-credit-reports.
                                

                                    Act fast: If you believe you're the victim of identity theft, there are several
                                    immediate steps you should take. If you're a LifeLock member and think you've been a
                                    victim, call our Member Services team for assistance at 1-800-LifeLock
                                    (1-800-543-3562).
                                


                                One other suggestion is to have fraud alerts placed on your credit file as an added
                                precaution during this time. If you would like to call and set the fraud alerts on your
                                own, please call one of the credit bureaus numbers listed below. Once fraud alerts are
                                placed with one bureau, they will notify the other two.
                            


                                    TransUnion: 1-800-680-7289
                                

                                    Experian: 1-888-397-3742
                                

                                    Equifax: 1-888-766-0008
                                


                                If you believe you’ve been a victim of identity theft, our Member Services team is
                                available at 1-800-LifeLock (1-800-543-3562) to assist at your convenience.
                            








                                I received a suspicious phone call, email or mail.
                            





                                Phone Call
                            

                                It is important to note that phone calls, like the one you received, can be phishing
                                schemes that criminals use to try to get your information. Unfortunately, LifeLock is
                                unable to assist with or investigate unwanted or suspicious phone calls such as these.
                                We recommend that you never give any personal or bank information over the phone unless
                                you are certain of the caller. You may want to contact your telephone service provider
                                to see if it is possible to block calls from this number.
                            

                                You may also contact your state Attorney General to file a consumer complaint regarding
                                these phone calls, as well as filing a complaint with the Federal Trade Commission. To
                                learn more about telephone fraud and report telephone fraud please go to www.ftc.gov/phonefraud.
                            

                                Another suggestion is to register your phone number on the national Do Not Call Registry
                                at www.DoNotCall.gov, or by calling
                                1-888-382-1222 (TTY: 1-866-290-4236) from the number you wish to register. If you
                                register online, you must click on the confirmation email you receive to complete your
                                free registration.
                            

                                Email
                            

                                Emails like the one you received may be phishing schemes that criminals use to try to
                                get your information. You should delete that email, do not reply or click any of the
                                links. Never give any personal or bank information over the Internet unless you are
                                certain of the sender.
                            

                                If you suspect you have been a victim of Internet Fraud, you can file a complaint with
                                the Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3) which is a partnership between the Federal
                                Bureau of Investigation (FBI), the National White Collar Crime Center (NW3C) and the
                                Bureau of Justice Assistance (BJA). IC3 accepts online Internet crime complaints from
                                either the person who believes they were defrauded or from a third party to the
                                complaint.
                            

                                Please visit www.ic3.gov for additional information.
                            

                                Mail
                            

                                Unfortunately, this is fairly common and does not necessarily mean that an identity
                                theft has occurred. LifeLock will be unable to stop or investigate this type of unwanted
                                mail. One suggestion is to mark the mail with "Return to Sender—Not at This Address" and
                                put it back into the mail. If you continue to receive mail that is not yours, please
                                notify the post office. If you are also receiving unwanted junk mail, you can opt out of
                                this online by visiting  www.dmachoice.org  and
                                filling out their online form.
                            

                                As always, watch your accounts carefully. If you notice any unauthorized activity on any
                                of your personal accounts, please notify LifeLock and the financial
                                institution/organization in question as soon as possible.
                            








                                How do I add a member?
                            





                                You can add additional members to your account online by clicking Manage Account.
                            

                                Scroll down until you see the button that says Add Member toward the right-hand side of
                                the screen. Then just enter the information requested.
                            

                                In rare cases, certain types of memberships cannot support adding members this way and
                                require a call to Member Services at 1-800-LifeLock (1-800-543-3562).
                            

                                Everyone has a different social security number, so we have to charge per person, per
                                membership, as this allows for each individual to receive our $1 Million Service
                                Guarantee. ‡ That means if you become a victim of identity theft while a LifeLock member
                                we will spend up to one million dollars to hire experts to help your recovery.
                            

                                ‡ Service Guarantee benefits for State of New York members are provided under a Master
                                Insurance Policy issued by State National Insurance Company. Benefits for all other
                                members are provided under a Master Insurance Policy underwritten by United Specialty
                                Insurance Company. Under the Service Guarantee LifeLock will spend up to $1 million to
                                hire experts to help your recovery.  Please see the policy for terms, conditions and
                                exclusions at LifeLock.com/legal.









                                Why can’t I access details of my household members’ accounts online?
                            





                                For security reasons, you will be unable to view or update the accounts for your whole
                                household through your own account. Each account holder needs to sign into their own
                                account in order to view or update their information.

                            

                                The reason we require separate online accounts for each adult member is because of the
                                sensitive personal information included on each member's account. We know it is
                                important to you to keep your personal information safe and so we share your personal
                                information only in accordance with our Privacy Policy.
                            

                                If anyone in your household has forgotten their username or password they can click Forgot User ID/Password
                                 and follow the instructions.
                            








                                Do you cover business entities or accounts?
                            





                                LifeLock does not cover businesses entities. Our technology and service is designed to
                                help protect individuals with social security numbers and other personal identifiable
                                information, which businesses don’t have.
                            












                                How do I update the credit card that I use to pay my LifeLock bill?
                            





                                You can update your credit card by clicking Billing Information.
                            

                                For security reasons, you’ll need to reenter the credit card number even if you are only
                                updating the expiration date.
                            








                                How do I check my LifeLock billing details?
                            





                                You can view your billing date and history by clicking Billing Information.
                            








                                How can I change my plan ?
                            





                                You can easily upgrade your account by clicking 
                                Manage Account and going to Upgrade Plan.
                            

                                If you would like to downgrade your plan, you can call us at 1-800-LifeLock
                                (1-800-543-3562), or by clicking 
                                Request Support and letting us know which plan you would like to switch to.
                            








                                How do I cancel my LifeLock account?
                            





                                We’ll be sorry to see you go! You can cancel over the phone at 1-800-LifeLock
                                (1-800-543-3562), or by clicking Request Support and
                                choosing that option.
                            












                                Where do I locate my credit reports and scores?
                            





                                You can find your information by clicking Credit Score & Report on the
                                left-hand side of the screen. Use the tabs at the top to view the different sections of
                                your credit report. You can scroll down in the Overview tab to download your credit
                                report.
                            

                                Only members on LifeLock Advantage, Ultimate, and Ultimate Plus plans who have passed
                                the appropriate authentication tests have access to these features—but if you’re a
                                LifeLock Standard member and would like to gain access, we’d be glad to help you change
                                plan tiers! Give us a call at 1-800-LifeLock (1-800-543-3562).
                            








                                Why is my LifeLock credit score different than what I've seen elsewhere?
                            





                                Some people are surprised to learn that there is no universal credit score; instead
                                there are many companies that apply many models—all based on your credit report data.
                                Each takes a slightly different approach to calculating a score. LifeLock uses the
                                VantageScore 3.0 ® model, which uses the same 300 to 850 range as the most familiar
                                scoring model, FICO, but may produce a slightly different number.
                            


                                    The credit score is intended for your own educational use. It is also commercially
                                    available to third parties along with numerous other credit scores and models in the
                                    marketplace. Please keep in mind third parties are likely to use a different score
                                    when evaluating your creditworthiness. Also, third parties will take into
                                    consideration items other than your credit score or information found in your credit
                                    file, such as your income.
                                









                                Who's who in credit?
                            





                                There are a variety of organizations involved in helping to assess your likelihood of
                                paying back money you’ve borrowed. To better understand credit, you need to begin by
                                understanding the various organizations and processes involved in determining whether to
                                offer you credit, and at what terms.
                                Here are the terms to know:
                            

                                What are Lenders?
                            

Lenders determine your creditworthiness by evaluating the information
                                on your credit profile. They also regularly contribute information about your loans—the
                                amount borrowed, whether you’ve made timely payments, and so on—to the three national
                                credit bureaus: Equifax, Experian and TransUnion.
                            

                                What are Credit Bureaus?
                            

                                The credit bureaus collect information from lenders and other data
                                sources, create a comprehensive credit report, and provide this data to potential
                                lenders and others that might need to assess your creditworthiness, such as landlords.
                            

                                What are Credit Reports?
                            

Credit reports, also known as credit files, are composed of the data a
                                credit bureau has gathered about you from lenders and other sources. Credit reports
                                include records of mortgage payments, credit card balances and payments, auto loan
                                payments and credit inquiries. It may also include public records, such as tax liens and
                                other information from government sources.
                            

                                What is a Credit Scoring Model?
                            

Credit scoring models are developed to provide a numerical
                                interpretation of the information in your credit report that has been tested to be
                                predictive. This gives lenders a statistical measurement of how likely you are to pay
                                back a loan. Some people are surprised to learn that there is no universal credit score;
                                instead there are many companies that apply many models—all based on your credit report
                                data. LifeLock uses a scoring model called VantageScore 3.0 ®, which uses the familiar
                                300-850 range. It's entirely healthy and routine for your credit scores to change
                                slightly, but generally a good idea to keep track of your score so you can notice any
                                dramatic shifts.
                            

                                Many people confuse credit reports with credit scores, but the two are quite different.
                                Understanding that difference can help you to figure out why you have a particular
                                score.
                            


                                    The credit score is intended for your own educational use. It is also commercially
                                    available to third parties along with numerous other credit scores and models in the
                                    marketplace. Please keep in mind third parties are likely to use a different score
                                    when evaluating your creditworthiness. Also, third parties will take into
                                    consideration items other than your credit score or information found in your credit
                                    file, such as your income.
                                









                                How is credit scored?
                            





                                A credit score is a three-digit number that results from a mathematical formula being
                                applied to your credit report. Credit scores may differ from one source to the next
                                because different lenders use different credit scoring models. And since a score is
                                based on frequently updated credit files, it may vary over time. It's entirely healthy
                                and routine for your credit scores to change slightly, but generally a good idea to keep
                                track of your score so you can notice any dramatic changes.
                            


                                    The credit score is intended for your own educational use. It is also commercially
                                    available to third parties along with numerous other credit scores and models in the
                                    marketplace. Please keep in mind third parties are likely to use a different score
                                    when evaluating your creditworthiness. Also, third parties will take into
                                    consideration items other than your credit score or information found in your credit
                                    file, such as your income.
                                









                                Why are there differences between my scores from each bureau?
                            





                                Because your scores are calculated using the information in your credit files, which may
                                differ across the three bureaus, there may be differences between the scores each bureau
                                provides. That's why it's important to periodically review your reports and scores from
                                all three agencies.
                            


                                    The credit score is intended for your own educational use. It is also commercially
                                    available to third parties along with numerous other credit scores and models in the
                                    marketplace. Please keep in mind third parties are likely to use a different score
                                    when evaluating your creditworthiness. Also, third parties will take into
                                    consideration items other than your credit score or information found in your credit
                                    file, such as your income.
                                









                                What should I do if there is an error on my credit report?
                            





                                If you believe the error is the result of fraud, or you just aren’t sure, contact us at
                                1-800-LifeLock (1-800-543-3562) immediately. If you think it was just a mistake, please
                                contact the creditor and the credit bureau directly to follow their dispute process.
                                It’s generally easier to file a dispute online. The three credit bureaus are:
                            

                                TransUnion: https://dispute.transunion.com
                                (you’ll have to make an account first); 800-680-7289
                                Experian: https://www.experian.com/disputes;
                                888-397-3742
                                Equifax: https://www.ai.equifax.com/CreditInvestigation;
                                888-766-0008
                            








                                Is LifeLock a credit monitoring service?
                            





                                Our LifeLock Ultimate Plus plan includes credit monitoring, but LifeLock is much more
                                than just credit monitoring alone. With credit monitoring you are only notified of
                                changes to your credit file, such as new loan applications, after they are reported to
                                the credit bureaus. The LifeLock alert network includes a variety of product features
                                and data sources and serves as a proactive link between consumers, lenders and
                                merchants. Although it is very extensive, our network does not cover all transactions at
                                all businesses, so you might not receive a LifeLock alert in every single case.
                            








                                Is LifeLock a credit repair organization?
                            





                                We want to be very clear that LifeLock is not a credit repair business. We’ll help
                                proactively safeguard your credit and finances, and if you become a victim of identity
                                theft while a LifeLock member, we’ll work to help you fix it—we’ll even spend up to $1
                                million on lawyers and experts if needed‡—but we don’t promise to repair your bad
                                credit, because that’s something we just can’t do.
                            

                                ‡ Service Guarantee benefits for State of New York members are provided under a Master
                                Insurance Policy issued by State National Insurance Company. Benefits for all other
                                members are provided under a Master Insurance Policy underwritten by United Specialty
